          "title": "Movement 3 — Restorative discipline in the church (vv.15-20)",
          "body": "Now Jesus pivots from how the strong treat the weak to how brothers treat each other when sin disrupts fellowship. The four-step procedure (private → two-or-three → ekklesia → separation) is the only place in the Gospels where the corporate disciplinary authority of the church is named explicitly. Each step seeks restoration; the goal-language is *gained your brother* (v.15, *kerdaino*). The binding/loosing promise (v.18, repeating 16:19 but now to the whole community) grants the church the authority to ratify on earth what heaven has already determined — the perfect-tense Greek forms (*shall have been bound*) are decisive. Verses 19-20 are not generic prayer-promises but the discipline section’s coda: even small gatherings exercising this authority do so in Christ’s presence and with the Father’s ratification."
